caption.text:
Good morning or afternoon! Over the weekend, I unboxed and sorted out the flower bulbs we’re planting this autumn. We’re planting some in containers, and most will be around the fruit trees in the backyard. 🌷🌼

Planting bulbs in the fall will create a gorgeous and colorful display of flowers that will provide an early source of nectar for pollinators and other wildlife in springtime!

Are you planting bulbs this season?

For information and education, visit flowerbulb.eu @flowerbulbsdotcom 

🪻🌷🪻🌷

caption.text:
Chef’s Choice Rosemary is an absolute gem with violet-blue flowers. It is known for its spicy flavor and aromatic scent due to its high oil content. It’s excellent for cooking and a perfect addition to kitchen gardens! At maturity, the plant height and width range from 18 to 24”. It’s hardy to zones 7b to 10b. 

Hello Darlin’ Blueberry has a low chill requirement (500-550 hours) and is hardy to zones 7a-9b. This gorgeous variety provides year-round interest with its transitioning foliage through the seasons and vivid pink flower buds. The medium-sized berries are sweet and flavorful!

I Declare Blueberry is another low-chill cultivar known for its pest and disease resistance and hardy to zones 7a-9b. This is an early variety and bears large, sweet berries! In the fall, the foliage turns to a gorgeous crimson. These blueberries are compact and dense, growing 4-5’ tall and 3-4’ wide. 

Osage Blackberry is thornless and has an upright clumping growth habit. It grows to 4-5′ high x 3-4′ wide and is hardy to zone 6-10. The fruits have an excellent, sweet flavor, are medium-sized, firm, and have good storage qualities, and the flowers attract pollinators.

I hope you found this helpful and that it inspires you to plant perennial crops this fall! 

To learn more about these beautiful plants, check out @southernlivingplantcollection .

Happy planting! 💚

caption.text:
Happy flower Friday! I planted miniature daffodils and a few double and fragrant varieties this year! Some were planted in containers and our backyard fruit garden. 

Are you planting daffodils, too? If so, which varieties? 

I’ve always been inspired by the beautiful ideas and information that @flowerbulbsdotcom shares. Check them out at Flowerbulb.eu.

Happy Fall Planting! 

🍁🌼🧡

caption.text:
Hello everyone! Over the weekend, we planted a bulb lawn in the backyard. To extend the season, we planted early to late-blooming varieties. We’re planting hyacinths, tulips, daffodils, early snow glories, crocuses, grape hyacinths, winter aconite, and Grecian windflowers. The smaller bulbs will be planted throughout the lawn and around the fruit trees!

In the Netherlands, this method of planting flower bulbs is called Stinzenplanten. This type of garden is centuries old and was cultivated with naturalizing wildflowers, both native and imported. These are considered stinzen plants or vintage bulbs and were introduced to Western Europe in the 16th century by explorers and botanists. 

Over time, these bulbs will increase, putting on a spectacular display of gorgeous blooms from late winter through spring and providing a food source for pollinators and other wildlife.

I’m excited for spring and can’t wait to show you the results. Stay tuned! 

Many thanks to Flowerbulb.eu for their partnership in this project.

To learn more about bulb lawns and for information and education, visit Flowerbulb.eu 
@flowerbulbsdotcom .

Happy planting! 

🌷🪻🌷🪻

caption.text:
Hello everyone! I hope you had a great weekend! I’ve been admiring these blueberry shrubs’ gorgeous ephemeral hues, which is another reason to plant them in your edible garden. Blueberries are delicious, nutrient-dense, and excellent sources of antioxidants that help protect and maintain healthy cell function.

The varieties featured in this video are Blueray, Duke, Chippewa, Bluejay, and Chandler. 

You can preorder bare root trees and shrubs for late winter through spring shipment. Please let me know in the comments if you’d like me to send you a link. 

Have a beautiful day! 

🫐🍁🍂🧣

caption.text:
These beautiful and delicious Lion’s mane (Hericium Erinaceus) were grown in hardwood sawdust (pellets) supplemented with bran. The bags are XL-sized, each block weighing a little over ten pounds. They were fruited in open air at temperatures between 63 and 65 F and a relative humidity of 62%. 

The incision was 3 inches long and was misted once daily before the pins or baby mushrooms emerged. (Primordia) 

Lion’s mane is delicate with a mild shellfish flavor, and it is meaty and juicy when cooked. It is nutritious, contains antioxidants, and is known to have anti-inflammatory properties. Based on research, it may boost the immune system, help with anxiety and depression, and is good for brain health. I encourage you to research to learn more about this beautiful mushroom!

This Lion’s Mane culture is quite impressive. It produces stunning, dense fruit bodies that are still fluffy! It’s also a prolific pinner! I got it from @mycrodexmushrooms

Happy mushroom growing!🍄‍🟫😍

➡️Instructions to make the block is 📌 in the comments. 

🍄‍🟫🍄🍄‍🟫🍄

caption.text:
👋🏽 I hope you’re having a good week! I wanted to share this year’s bulb lasagna!🌼🌷

Lasagna planting creates a beautiful display of continuous spring blooms by planting early, mid, and late-flowering varieties in layers. The bulbs are planted at proper depths, with the latest blooming at the bottom layer. Consider taller varieties like Darwin Hybrid tulips or Trumpet Daffodils, which will display better when planted deepest. This method originated in the Netherlands and was developed by Dutch bulb mavens or experts. 

Will you be planting a lasagna garden this autumn? If so, which varieties are you most excited about?

For education and information, check out flowerbulb.eu.  @flowerbulbsdotcom

Planting information is in the comment section below.

music_asset_info.title: Background Inspirational

caption.text:
Here’s one of our favorite mushrooms! The beautiful King Oyster, Pleurotus eryngii, prefers cold fruiting conditions (55-65 F) with 8-12 hours indirect sunlight or supplemental lighting. This delicious mushroom possesses numerous health benefits and is rich in nutrients and antioxidants! It has the texture of scallops and a mild shellfish flavor. Some say it tastes like abalone! 

The stems (stipes) were sliced into 1/4-inch rounds, sauteed in olive oil, and minced garlic and butter added towards the end of cooking. They were seasoned with sea salt.😋

I hope you’re having a good week! ❤️🍄‍🟫
